commits.subject: In the previous commit, we created a product Resolver. But we changed
commits.message:
In the previous commit, we created a product Resolver. But we changed
the return value to the generic Product Resolved. { product, error}.

If we look at the product module, we see that the the routing has to
go through a resolve propety. Like graph ql, a resolver Class resolves all
the data into resolvedData.

We assume that the ResolverClass has done it's mapping job.
with bundles it into our product error object stream.

In our detail component, the data is already inside the snapshot data property.
Accessing the data array from the activated route service gives us a reference
to the data instance. All code that changes that resolveData array is shared
with anyone that is linked via this.activeroute.snashop.data...
All folks linked to the same activeRoute will be privy to that datachange.
Our resolver works with a stored activated Route snapshot. That's our source.

commits.author: mariomui
commits.subject: Create a product resolver service
commits.message:
Create a product resolver service

Reference Personal Notes
[Resolver Notes](:note:e4d8cbd4-e575-4f00-858c-f13a987ee815)
This resolver is based on intercepting the request for data via the activated
Link and the component. This service is placed in core because of
https://itnext.io/choosing-a-highly-scalable-folder-structure-in-angular-d987de65ec7
where it explains how to create a scalable directory for angular
* “Structure the app such that you can locate code quickly”
*  “Have a near-term view of implementation and a long-term vision.
* Start small but keep in mind where the app is heading down the road”.

The SharedModule is where any shared components,
* pipes/filters
* services should go.
The SharedModule can be imported in any other module when those items will be re-used.
The shared module shouldn’t have any dependency to the rest of the application
and should therefore not rely on any other module.

The CoreModule takes on the role of the root AppModule ,
but is not the module which gets bootstrapped by Angular at run-time.
The CoreModule should contain singleton services (which is usually the case),
universal components and other features where there’s only once instance
 per application. To prevent re-importing the core module elsewhere,
 you should also add a guard for it in the core module’ constructor.

 This resolver is a singleton service as will a majority of the services
 you choose.

commits.subject: Allow the filtered results to be shown after clicking away (ALT)
commits.message:
Allow the filtered results to be shown after clicking away (ALT)

The url changes hitting our client js. We retain our queryParams but
our productList has to listen for it. Since url paths are being switched,
this means that the product onInit fires. The params will not change here
as the only way to change params is through another activated link for
which there is none.
Instead of using observables, we use snapshots unlike our previous commit.

commits.author: mariomui
commits.subject: Allow the filtered results to be shown after clicking away
commits.message:
Allow the filtered results to be shown after clicking away

The filter query and is Image shown on product List are state.
They are brough over by the activated link on the product name.
As such they are brough over as query params. Pressing and activating
the back button link on our product detail view should retain these params
over to the new path /products. We do this with queryParamsHandling

In the view we set the `queryParamsHandling="preserve"` as an attribute
in the js we do
```
this.router.navigate(['product'], {
  queryParamsHandling: true
})
```

In additional, when the query params are preserved, the product list must
listen to these changes and change the initial props. ngzone will see that
the starter proteins are scarred and generate renders based on that value.
filter subscripte, then populate our listfilter and showImages starterproteins

A good way to grok the get and set pattern they use for listfilter is that
it's a good way to remove the (). Think of it as a .length property on an
array.

commits.subject: Hook up product edit view to edit changes.
commits.message:
Hook up product edit view to edit changes.

Here the navbar has a button that will change the params. Expected behavior
is to change the view. We could change the inital product property of the
component via a button on the current component but the navbar only has
access to changes to params. This is a good time to use Observables
so we can have the function to initialize this.product refire on params
change.

commits.author: mariomui
commits.subject: A treatise on the myriad ways to obtain url paramaters
commits.message:
A treatise on the myriad ways to obtain url paramaters

Getting asynchronous data should be done on the onInit. Constructor is
for depenedency injection and setting up initial props.

The active Route on the component allows us to see the current url.
We can use snapshot to obtain a non observable (snapshot) of our data.
Or we can use the observable pattern which will listen to all changes to
active route. In this use case where the view should always proceed with
data from an immediate action, Observables her is over kill. Observables
are used to centralize code and to respond to changes from other components
such as managing global modal states.

commits.subject: Modularize app routing into a feature module
commits.message:
Modularize app routing into a feature module

Exporting the RouterModule allows the declared components in the app
module to have access to the routing methods like navigate.

Routes are frequently tampered with and should be kept distinct from the
main module manager.

commits.author: mariomui
commits.subject: Comment on why there is an explicitly defined routing module
commits.message:
Comment on why there is an explicitly defined routing module

Explicilty routed modules are lower priority inserted. They are imported
after the regular inserted modules no matter the order.
